 We resolve this by migrating the sieve entirely to the device via tiled sieve segment kernel,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" The segment is divided into tiles of 32 ,768 odd numbers, each represented as a 4 KB bitset, sized to fit comfortably within the 48 KB of L1 shared memory available per Streaming Multiprocessor (SM) on Ada Lovelace and Blackwell architectures, while leaving headroom for the thread block’s register file and simultaneously- resident tiles","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Each tile is loaded directly into shared memory ( sh tile), and GPU threads collaboratively sieve it using a permanently resident, read-only array of base primes","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Once a tile is fully sieved, coalesced writes flush the result to the global VRAM segment buffer","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 This design eliminates PCIe transfers from the critical path,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Per segment, the CPU issues only an 8-byte atomic starting index and receives a 4-byte result from the device-side reduction kernel","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" During Phase 1, the host uploads the current batch of small primes to a device staging buffer (d p batch); for the experiment parameters (PSMALL = 106, PBATCH = 2×106), with PSMALL corresponding to 78 498 primes, each batch consists of min(78 498, PBATCH) × 8 bytes ≈ 628 KB, a constant per-segment overhead that replaces the variable 14 MB segment bitset transfer of the v1 architecture [ 4]","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Operationally, the count unverified kernel evaluates the results directly in device memory","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Rather than employing a complex shared-memory reduction tree, it uses a flat, per-thread atomicAdd to accumulate unverified entries into a single 32-bit counter","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Because empirical results show that Phase 1 verification practically never fails, this branch is virtually never taken, meaning global atomic contention is zero","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" The kernel writes this scalar result into a preallocated buffer, and the host retrieves this value via a single cudaMemcpyAsync call (with a 3","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
"subsequent stream synchronisation to ensure the scalar is visible before the conditional branch), determining whether Phase 2 must be invoked","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" Figure 2 gives a comprehensive view of the system’s memory boundaries, threading model, and kernel execution flow for a single GPU worker","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" During initialisation, the host allocates device memory and issues an asynchronous host →device copy of the small -primes bitset and supporting arrays; these structures remain resident and read -only on the device for the worker’s lifetime","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" The host spawns one std::thread per physical GPU, each binding to a distinct GPU context and coordinating work via a 64 -bit atomic counter ( g next seg start) claimed with fetch add","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" In steady state the GPU executes entirely on-device, building tiled segment bitsets in L1 shared memory and running a device -side reduction kernel ( count unverified kernel) that writes a small integer result","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" If the reduction reports any unverified entries, the pipeline performs a PCIe device →host transfer and the host invokes the Phase -2 CPU resolver; if the reduction reports zero, execution follows the zero-copy fast path and avoids PCIe traversal","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 The diagram also shows the Phase -2 resolution path that returns control to the worker loop and the abort path used for unrecoverable failures,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
