 Lagrange’s Theorem  2,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
1,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
 Definitions and Lemmas  This section is devoted to present three definitions and lemmas that will be used in the paper [5],Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Definition 1 (subgroup),Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
 A subgroup is a special nonempty subset of a group,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" A nonempty subset  𝑀 of a group 𝑁 is regarded as a subgroup of 𝑁 if the multiplication of 𝑁 also becomes a group,  denoted as 𝑀 ≤  𝑁",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Definition 2 (Coset),Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" A simple example illustrates that 𝑁 is a group, 𝑀 is a subgroup of 𝑁, and  𝑛 is an element of 𝑁",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Then 𝑁𝑀 =  {𝑚: for all 𝑚 ∈  𝑀} denotes the left companion set of 𝑀, and  𝑀𝑁 =  {𝑚𝑛: for all 𝑚 ∈  𝑀} denotes the right companion set of 𝑀",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
"  Only the subgroup that generates the ""companion set"" can form a group, and only the set that  contains the unit element can form a group, and the companion set does not contain the unit element,  so of course, it cannot form a group, so it is called ""companion set""",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Definition 3 (finite group),Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Let 𝐾 be a group, and if 𝑛 is a finite set, then it is called a finite  group",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
 The finite set consists of the set of those natural numbers less than or equal to a natural number  𝑧,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" It is called a line segment of the natural numbers string and is denoted by symbol |1, 𝑧|",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
   Lemma 1,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" If a finite order 𝑚 has a group 𝑁, then each of the orders of any 𝑎 ∈  𝑁 can be figured  out with the order of 𝑁, where 𝑎𝐾 = 𝑒",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Proof,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" In group 𝑁, these elements are distinct and constitute a subgroup",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Since 𝑝 is the order of  the subgroup, so is it the divisor",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Hence, k =  𝑛𝑝 and 𝑎𝑘 = 𝑎𝑧𝑝 = (𝑎𝑝)𝑧 = 𝑒",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Lemma 2,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" If the order of a finite group 𝑁 is of prime order, then it has no proper subgroup",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Proof,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
 Consider a group 𝑁 and denote its prime order as 𝑚,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Now, 𝑚 has only two factors 1 and  𝑚",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
 Let the prime order of the group 𝑁 be m,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Now, 𝑘 can only find two factors, 1 and 𝑘",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" Therefore,  it is known that the subgroups of 𝑁 are {𝑒} and 𝑁 itself",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
" In summary, no suitable subgroup exists",Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
  Lemma 3,Lagranges_Theorem_in_Group_Theory_Proof_and_Appli
