"1) where E′ is the energy of the virtual intermediate state, and so diver ges if the theory is extrapolated to arbitrarily high energies",string theory
 There are two main possibilities,string theory
" The ﬁrst is that the theory has a nontrivial ultraviolet ﬁxed point and is ﬁne at high energy , the divergences being an artifact of naive perturbation 44",string theory
theory ,string theory
 The second is that there is new physics at some energy and the extrapolation of the low energy theory beyond this point is invalid,string theory
 The existence of a nontrivial ﬁxed point is hard to determine ,string theory
" One of the usual tools, Monte Carlo simulation, is extremely diﬃcult because of the need to retain coordinate in- variance in the discretized theory ",string theory
" Expansion around the cr itical dimension d= 2 indicates a nontrivial UV ﬁxed point when gravity is coupled to certain kinds of matter, but it is impossible to say whether this persists to d= 4",string theory
" 1 The more common expectation, based in part on experience (su ch as the weak inter- action), is that the nonrenormalizability indicates a brea kdown of the theory , and that at short distances we will ﬁnd a new theory in which the interact ion is spread out in space- time in some way that cuts oﬀ the divergence",string theory
" At this point the condensed matter half of the audience is thinking, “OK, so put the thing on a lattice",string theory
” But it is not so easy ,string theory
" W e know that Lorentz invariance holds to very good approximati on in the low energy theory , and that means that if we spread the interaction in space we sp read it in time as well, with consequent loss of causality or unitarity ",string theory
 Moreover we know that we have local coordi- nate invariance in nature—this makes it even harder to sprea d the interaction out without producing inconsistencies,string theory
" In fact, we know of only one way to spread out the gravitationa l interaction and cut oﬀ the divergence without spoiling the consistency of the theo ry ",string theory
" That way is string theory , in which the graviton and all other elementary particles are on e-dimensional objects, strings, rather than points as in quantum ﬁeld theory ",string theory
" Why this should work and not anything else is not at all obvious a priori, but as we develop the theor y we will see that if we try to make a consistent Lorentz-invariant quantum theory of st rings we are led inevitably to include gravity [45], [46], and that the short distance dive rgences of ﬁeld theory are no longer present",string theory
"2 Perhaps we merely suﬀer from a lack of imagination, and there are many other consistent theories of gravity with a short-distance cutoﬀ",string theory
